essage =E2=80=9Cthis stuff will probably go up=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and =
that information is valuable.If you are a trader, another =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sk=
ill? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0you might have is buying stuff that will go=C2=A0down. =
You keep saying =E2=80=9Cooh this stock is poised to go to the moon,=E2=80=
=9D you buy it, it goes to zero. This skill seems somehow more attainable t=
han the first skill,=C2=A0though it=E2=80=99s not clear that that=E2=80=99s=
 actually true.
  [2]
 It is harder to make money with this skill. If you buy stuff, and it goes =
down, and you sell it, you will have less=C2=A0money.Oh, I know, I know, yo=
u can try the George Costanza approach: Any time you think you should buy a=
 stock, you sell it instead. But this seems tricky to do yourself; it requi=
res not only the self-knowledge to say =E2=80=9CI keep getting things wrong=
=E2=80=9D but also the ability to continually analyze your instincts to ide=
ntify the valuable=C2=A0signal. =E2=80=9CAfter extensive research and analy=
sis, I want to buy this stock, which means I should sell it,=E2=80=9D you t=
hink, but what if actually that is the=C2=A0impulse you should be resisting=
? How do you know where to stop your conscious analysis and do the opposite=
 of the result?
  [3]
Can you monetize the skill in other ways? I think if you have a strong trac=
k record and a rigorous repeatable process of only buying stocks that go do=
wn, you really=C2=A0should=C2=A0be able to start a newsletter or get hired =
by a hedge fund to tell people your best ideas (so they can short them), bu=
t again I think this is tricky in practice. Probably if you waltz in the do=
or at Citadel and are like =E2=80=9Chi my superpower is that I am exception=
ally terrible at picking stocks=E2=80=9D they will have doubts. I bet there=
=E2=80=99s some sell-side equity research analyst out there who is kept on =
the payroll for making reliably wrong stock picks, but it can=E2=80=99t be =
that common.Can other people free-ride on your skill? Can they look at your=
 track record and say =E2=80=9Ceverything this person picks goes down, so I=
 should short it=E2=80=9D? I mean! Tuttle Capital Management once launched =
some very rude exchange-traded funds to fade Jim Cramer=E2=80=99s and Cathi=
e Wood=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock picks, but I don=E2=80=99t think those had any =
real alpha; it is not actually the case that Cramer or Wood has this sort o=
f anti-skill. In general, if your stock picks are known=C2=A0broadly, they=
=E2=80=99re probably not bad enough to make betting against you a reliable =
strategy.On the other hand,=C2=A0your=C2=A0broker=C2=A0probably knows (1) w=
hat you=E2=80=99re buying and (2) how you=E2=80=99re doing. If you=E2=80=99=
re terrible, your broker might be tempted.=C2=A0Here is a funny CME Group d=
isciplinary action against a futures broker called Wing Fung Futures Limite=
d:Pursuant to an offer of settlement in which Wing Fung Futures Limited (=
=E2=80=9CWing Fung=E2=80=9D) neither admitted nor denied the rule violation=
s or factual findings upon which the penalty is based, on July 16, 2024, a =
Panel of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Business Conduct Committee (=E2=80=
=9CPanel=E2=80=9D) found that between July 22, 2020, and July 7, 2022, Wing=
 Fung deployed an automated trading system (=E2=80=9CATS=E2=80=9D) in the A=
ustralian Dollar, British Pound, Canadian Dollar, Euro FX, Japanese Yen, Ne=
w Zealand Dollar, E-mini NASDAQ, Micro E-mini NASDAQ, and E-mini S&P 500 fu=
tures markets wherein the ATS=E2=80=99s strategy was to submit orders based=
 upon trades executed by its clients who were regularly unprofitable. Speci=
fically, upon a target client establishing a short/long position, the ATS g=
enerated a trading signal to enter an order in the same market for the same=
 price and quantity as the client, though to establish the opposite short/l=
ong position. The Panel found that by employing this strategy, Wing Fung at=
tempted to profit from its knowledge of its clients=E2=80=99 record of loss=
es, which was not available to others in the marketplace. Additionally, the=
 Panel found that Wing Fung employees used Wing Fung=E2=80=99s clients=E2=
=80=99 unique operator IDs to enter orders into Globex. The Panel further f=
ound that Wing Fung=E2=80=99s leadership fundamentally did not understand, =
or were otherwise completely unaware, of Exchange rules that prohibited the=
 activity described above. Therefore, the Panel found that Wing Fung failed=
 to diligently supervise its employees and agents.I will say that in genera=
l if you are a client-facing foreign currency=C2=A0firm, and your clients a=
re terrible at trading currencies, it is often a good and legitimate=C2=A0s=
trategy to=C2=A0internalize their orders: If they want to buy 10,000 Austra=
lian dollars for US dollars, you=C2=A0sell=C2=A0them the Aussie=C2=A0from y=
our own account, so that you are naturally on the other side of their order=
s and make money when they lose money.
  [4]
 But I suppose if you=E2=80=99re a broker who sends client orders=C2=A0to t=
he exchange, and you also send=C2=A0your=C2=A0own=C2=A0opposite orders to t=
he exchange to fade them, that looks rude.
