      Crypto is for fun
   =20
 =20
I wrote in 2021 that =E2=80=9CCrypto Markets Are Where the Fun Is=E2=80=9D:=
If you work on Wall Street =E2=80=94 particularly as a derivatives structur=
er or high-frequency trading developer or securities lawyer =E2=80=94 you a=
ctually like this stuff. You are there because you are fascinated by struct=
ure, because you enjoy puzzling out the technical details of these mechanis=
ms and trying to find new ways to push on them. In traditional finance this=
 is all sort of saturated and competitive: Not only is it hard to get rich =
by coming up with a new derivative structure or trading algorithm, but it=
=E2=80=99s hard to even get the intellectual satisfaction of doing that, be=
cause so much of what is possible has already been done, and innovation ten=
ds to be technical and incremental. Whereas in crypto it can feel like more=
 of a blank slate, or at least, like a different foundation where it takes =
ingenuity to re-erect the old structures.There is a sweet spot, though. If =
you have spent the last 20 years working in equity market structure, you mi=
ght=C2=A0know=C2=A0too much to start over in the crypto sandbox. Your deep =
knowledge is a source of competitive advantage and Fingerspitzengef=C3=BChl=
; you will=C2=A0enjoy=C2=A0making technical and incremental improvements, w=
hile you would find it tedious to have to relearn a new market structure fr=
om scratch, and you might find crypto=E2=80=99s newer market structure naiv=
e and annoying.=C2=A0For a while, the right trade was apparently: If you ru=
n a successful experienced trading firm, you get the=C2=A0interns=C2=A0to t=
rade crypto. Here is a Fortune story=C2=A0by Leo Schwartz about the rise an=
d fall of Jump Crypto, the division of Jump Trading Group that was once run=
 by Kanav Kariya:In late 2015,=C2=A0Jump=C2=A0had created=C2=A0a research a=
nd development office at its founders=E2=80=99 alma mater, sponsoring resea=
rch projects and working with professors on futuristic projects, like using=
 virtual reality headsets to mimic trading environments. They would also hi=
re university students as interns, finding potential stars by word of mouth=
. A friend referred Kariya, who started as a student at Jump=E2=80=99s coll=
ege satellite.=C2=A0Jump=C2=A0had a conundrum. The firm needed to test the =
mettle of its would-be staffers=E2=80=94whether they could parse the nuance=
s in financial markets and translate them into algorithmic trading models. =
But it couldn=E2=80=99t give the temporary hires the keys to the kingdom, w=
ith its proprietary strategies and billions of dollars in capital.=C2=A0Cry=
pto offered a solution. The sector had its own tradable assets, exchanges, =
and quirks, but it was separated enough from Jump=E2=80=99s world of stocks=
 and bonds that it wouldn=E2=80=99t pose a threat. =E2=80=9CIt was a bit of=
 a toy market,=E2=80=9D says one former employee, who spoke with=C2=A0Fortu=
ne=C2=A0on the condition of anonymity to discuss their previous firm. ...So=
 when Kariya joined as an intern in January 2017, he was assigned to build =
early crypto trading infrastructure for the firm=E2=80=94with little oversi=
ght. =E2=80=9CWe could just go out and do our own thing,=E2=80=9D he would =
tell a podcast in January 2023. =E2=80=9CWork under this fully encapsulated=
 bubble.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It feels like a useful mental model for crypto: Cryp=
to is what you get when you take the smart ambitious interns at traditional=
 financial firms and put them in charge of their own play=C2=A0market. Only=
 for real money.This is true in a deeper sense. In many cases, the essentia=
l attribute of a crypto token is=C2=A0liquidity:=C2=A0What you want, often,=
 is a token that trades a lot, because your goal for the token is to trade =
it a lot. Real-world utility, a sensible business model,=C2=A0acceptance in=
 real transactions, etc., are all less important than just=C2=A0trading, if=
 you think of=C2=A0crypto as a toy market for traders to play with. If a to=
ken trades a lot at a high price, that in itself=C2=A0justifies the price, =
because that is all that is asked of a token: It doesn=E2=80=99t need to ha=
ve a good underlying business or cash flows; it just has to trade a lot=C2=
=A0at a high price.And so Jump was, for a while, critical to the crypto eco=
nomy, because it was a big market maker, so it could ensure that tokens wou=
ld trade a lot. Since that was what created value, Jump could=C2=A0make=C2=
=A0tokens valuable. In exchange for that service, token creators would give=
 Jump some of the tokens, and Jump would then have an incentive to make the=
m valuable:Token projects will lend market makers a large supply of tokens =
so they can kickstart trading. Some firms also negotiate a call option, whi=
ch gives the market makers the right to buy a chunk of the tokens for a ste=
ep discount if the project goes well. Selig says that the inverted structur=
e in crypto=E2=80=94where market makers work with token projects, rather th=
an exchanges=E2=80=94makes some sense, given projects=E2=80=99 need to spur=
 trading activity. It also creates dynamics that would never be allowed in =
TradFi. While crypto market makers still make money off the trading spreads=
, the massive windfalls often come from those lucrative call options.=C2=A0=
For a firm like=C2=A0Jump, becoming the market maker for a token project me=
ant unlimited upside with no real financial risk. =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99r=
e at=C2=A0Jump, you decide which one is going to win,=E2=80=9D one crypto e=
xchange founder tells=C2=A0Fortune, speaking on the condition of anonymity =
to discuss industry dynamics.Man, what a crazy time the crypto boom was. It=
 really did teach a generation of young financial traders that they could b=
uild perpetual motion machines: You make a token, you trade it, that makes =
it go up, the value comes from you trading it, you can do no wrong, you get=
 rich, =E2=80=9Cunlimited upside with no real financial risk.=E2=80=9D One =
token that Jump made valuable was Luna, which brought the whole thing down.
  [5]

