      Ozempic is [good/bad] for business
   =20
 =20
I have had fun around here imagining that GLP-1 agonist weight loss drugs (=
Ozempic, Wegovy, etc.) are =E2=80=9Cuniversal demand suppressants=E2=80=9D =
that make their users so content and disciplined that they stop consuming a=
nything else. If it were true, this would have weird economic effects: Drug=
 companies could charge a lot for Ozempic, nobody else could charge a lot f=
or anything, overall corporate profits might go down, and diversified share=
holders, harmed by this, might call up the drug companies and say =E2=80=9C=
hey, we are your owners, you=E2=80=99re losing us so much money, stop makin=
g these profitable drugs.=E2=80=9DBut of course this is all a thought exper=
iment; it=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t actually happen. In fact, if everyone eats f=
ewer snacks and gets healthier, that increases demand for many things: Peop=
le might exercise more, buy more airplane tickets (while using less jet fue=
l when they fly), live longer and consume stuff into older age, etc. Anothe=
r way to imagine GLP-1 drugs is that they are, like, demand quality sorters=
: They make their users demand more good stuff and less bad stuff; they enh=
ance their willpower so they buy more stuff that they should=C2=A0want and =
fewer guilty pleasures. And so the GLP-1 trade is, like, =E2=80=9Clong comp=
anies that make good stuff and short companies that make bad stuff.=E2=80=
=9DHere, via Tyler Cowen, is a Meatingplace article
  [6]
=C2=A0on the sorting:Lean protein =E2=80=9Cemerged as the biggest winner=E2=
=80=9D on supermarket shelves among shoppers who have taken popular new wei=
ght-loss drugs, according to a report using consumer surveys.Data analytics=
 firm Grocery Doppio=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CState of Digital Grocery Performanc=
e Scorecard: H1 2024=E2=80=9D found reduced grocery spending among 97% of c=
onsumers who had taken GLP-1 medications =E2=80=94 glucagon-like peptide-1 =
receptor agonists, including semaglutide drugs Ozempic, Rybelsus and Wegovy=
, prescribed for diabetes or obesity.Their grocery bills were down by an av=
erage of 11%, yet they spent 27% more on lean proteins from lean meat, eggs=
 and seafood. Other gainers were meal replacements (19%), healthy snacks (1=
7%), whole fruits and vegetables (13%) and sports and energy drinks (7%).Sn=
acks and soda took the brunt of reduced spending by consumers after GLP-1 t=
reatment: snacks and confectionary (-52%), prepared baked goods (-47%), sod=
a/sugary beverages (-28%), alcoholic beverages (-17%) and processed food (-=
13%).Lower overall grocery bills is the main point, but it=E2=80=99s a good=
 time to be selling whole fruits and vegetables and a bad time to be sellin=
g snacks and confectionary.Elsewhere, here is a New York Times story about =
addictive microtransactions in sports video games:To encourage players to s=
pend money, Electronic Arts and 2K have made the experience of virtually op=
ening card packs as appealing as possible. A tiny dopamine rush triggers a =
desire to buy even more.Jamie Madigan, a psychologist who specializes in vi=
deo games, said these systems operated on the same principle of random rewa=
rds as slot machines. The anticipation is more important than the reward it=
self.=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s been research,=E2=80=9D Madigan said, =E2=80=
=9Cto show that the exciting part isn=E2=80=99t finding out what=E2=80=99s =
in the box, but before you open the box =E2=80=94 seeing the little effects=
 pop up, hearing the sounds, watching the opening animations.=E2=80=9DIf GL=
P-1 drugs are not universal demand suppressants=C2=A0but universal willpowe=
r enhancers,=C2=A0eventually there will be studies of the effect of Ozempic=
 on videogame microtransactions, won=E2=80=99t there? I=E2=80=99m excited f=
or that.
