      Harvard
   =20
 =20
Harvard University is basically in the business of brand alliances. Harvard=
 has a very strong academic brand, so=C2=A0that =E2=80=9CI went to Harvard=
=E2=80=9D is widely assumed to convey =E2=80=9CI am smart.=E2=80=9D (Disclo=
sure, sorry, I went to Harvard.) But then it also wants to partner with oth=
er people who have other good but less academic brands: It wants=C2=A0some=
=C2=A0people to be associated with Harvard not because they have high test =
scores but because they are famous actors or great athletes or rich. Those =
people bring Harvard=E2=80=99s brand to a wider audience, which helps Harva=
rd attract smart students and famous professors who think =E2=80=9Cah cool =
I get to be around celebrities and rich people, that will probably be fun a=
nd also good for my career.=E2=80=9D (The rich people also give Harvard mon=
ey.) And the celebrities and rich people=C2=A0want to attach their brand to=
 Harvard=E2=80=99s, because Harvard has that good academic brand, and peopl=
e want to look smart.The trick is to do this in a way that is cynical=C2=A0=
enough=C2=A0to maximize impact, but not too=C2=A0cynical; you have to maint=
ain the core academic brand.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s a fun Bloomberg Businesswe=
ek article about a Harvard Business School marketing professor who, unsurpr=
isingly, is very good at this:Anita Elberse =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is best known fo=
r her course The Business of Entertainment, Media, and Sports=E2=80=94or #B=
EMS to its alumni who post about it on Instagram and LinkedIn. The four-day=
, $12,000 program, an elective open to professionals not enrolled at HBS, h=
as become a blockbuster for the university. Elberse=E2=80=99s case studies,=
 ranging from=C2=A0David Beckham=E2=80=99s brand management to=C2=A0Beyonc=
=C3=A9=E2=80=99s music launch strategies, are often announced like an album=
 drop on social media. Which is why, along with execs from Hollywood and Ma=
dison Avenue, stars such as=C2=A0Channing Tatum=C2=A0and=C2=A0LL Cool J=C2=
=A0have signed up, hoping to build the next celebrity business empire.Its a=
ppeal isn=E2=80=99t just that it allows C-level normies to study alongside =
celebrities but also that it allows famous people to feel like Ivy Leaguers=
. =E2=80=9CThis week I got accepted into Harvard! Words cannot describe my =
excitement!=E2=80=9D posted singer Ciara online after getting into Elberse=
=E2=80=99s program in 2019. =E2=80=9CCourse complete!=E2=80=9D declared Fix=
er Upper moguls Chip and Joanna Gaines on Instagram the same year, next to =
a photo of the couple wearing Harvard letter sweaters and holding up diplom=
as. (Elberse later wrote a case on their Magnolia Network.) =E2=80=A6This y=
ear marks the program=E2=80=99s 10th anniversary. Elberse says the more it =
grows in popularity, the more she has to guard against celebs co-opting the=
 Harvard brand to further their own. =E2=80=9CWe sometimes say =E2=80=98no=
=E2=80=99 to people if I don=E2=80=99t get a sense they=E2=80=99re here for=
 the right reasons,=E2=80=9D she says. =E2=80=9CThis is not about you takin=
g photos walking around the Harvard campus.=E2=80=9DI mean, it is a little =
bit, right? Like if you have a lot of Instagram followers and you post your=
self in a Harvard sweater walking around the campus, that is just good for =
everyone=E2=80=99s business.
