=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">futures broker</a> called Wing Fung Futures Limited:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pursuant to an offer of settlement in wh=
ich Wing Fung Futures Limited (=E2=80=9CWing Fung=E2=80=9D) neither admitte=
d nor denied the rule violations or factual findings upon which the penalty=
 is based, on July 16, 2024, a Panel of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Bus=
iness Conduct Committee (=E2=80=9CPanel=E2=80=9D) found that between July 2=
2, 2020, and July 7, 2022, Wing Fung deployed an automated trading system (=
=E2=80=9CATS=E2=80=9D) in the Australian Dollar, British Pound, Canadian Do=
llar, Euro FX, Japanese Yen, New Zealand Dollar, E-mini NASDAQ, Micro E-min=
i NASDAQ, and E-mini S&amp;P 500 futures markets wherein the ATS=E2=80=99s =
strategy was to submit orders based upon trades executed by its clients who=
 were regularly unprofitable. Specifically, upon a target client establishi=
ng a short/long position, the ATS generated a trading signal to enter an or=
der in the same market for the same price and quantity as the client, thoug=
h to establish the opposite short/long position. The Panel found that by em=
ploying this strategy, Wing Fung attempted to profit from its knowledge of =
its clients=E2=80=99 record of losses, which was not available to others in=
 the marketplace. Additionally, the Panel found that Wing Fung employees us=
ed Wing Fung=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=99 unique operator IDs to enter orders=
 into Globex. The Panel further found that Wing Fung=E2=80=99s leadership f=
undamentally did not understand, or were otherwise completely unaware, of E=
xchange rules that prohibited the activity described above. Therefore, the =
Panel found that Wing Fung failed to diligently supervise its employees and=
 agents.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I will say that in ge=
neral if you are a client-facing foreign currency=C2=A0firm, and your clien=
ts are terrible at trading currencies, it is often a good and legitimate=C2=
=A0strategy to=C2=A0<em>internalize </em>their orders: If they want to buy =
10,000 Australian dollars for US dollars, you=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>them =
the Aussie=C2=A0from your own account, so that you are naturally on the oth=
er side of their orders and make money when they lose money.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> But I suppose if you=E2=80=99re a broker who sends client orders=C2=A0=
to the exchange, and you also send=C2=A0your=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>opposit=
e orders to the exchange to fade them, that looks rude.</p><table class=3D"=
