5px;">Crypto is for fun</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I wrote in 2021 that =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36145613.193392/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTEvY3J5cHRvLW1h=
cmtldHMtYXJlLXdoZXJlLXRoZS1mdW4taXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcyMjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNzIyJnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe548a1ad" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Crypt=
o Markets Are Where the Fun Is</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">If you work on Wall Street =E2=80=94 particularly as a deriva=
tives structurer or high-frequency trading developer or securities lawyer =
=E2=80=94 you actually like this stuff. You are there because you are fasci=
nated by structure, because you enjoy puzzling out the technical details of=
 these mechanisms and trying to find new ways to push on them. In tradition=
al finance this is all sort of saturated and competitive: Not only is it ha=
rd to get rich by coming up with a new derivative structure or trading algo=
rithm, but it=E2=80=99s hard to even get the intellectual satisfaction of d=
oing that, because so much of what is possible has already been done, and i=
nnovation tends to be technical and incremental. Whereas in crypto it can f=
eel like more of a blank slate, or at least, like a different foundation wh=
ere it takes ingenuity to re-erect the old structures.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a sweet spot, though. If you have spent t=
he last 20 years working in equity market structure, you might=C2=A0know<em=
>=C2=A0</em>too much to start over in the crypto sandbox. Your deep knowled=
ge is a source of competitive advantage and <em>Fingerspitzengef=C3=BChl</e=
m>; you will=C2=A0<em>enjoy=C2=A0</em>making technical and incremental impr=
ovements, while you would find it tedious to have to relearn a new market s=
tructure from scratch, and you might find crypto=E2=80=99s newer market str=
ucture naive and annoying.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a whil=
e, the right trade was apparently: If you run a successful experienced trad=
ing firm, you get the=C2=A0<em>interns=C2=A0</em>to trade crypto. Here is <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36145613.193392/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9mb3J0dW5lLmNvbS8yMDI0LzA3LzExL2p1bXAtdHJhZGluZy1rYW5hdi1rYXJpeWEtY3=
J5cHRvLXRlcnJhLWRvLWt3b24tZGlzYXN0ZXI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe6a74c99" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">a Fortune story</a>=C2=A0by Leo Schwartz about the rise and fall of J=
ump Crypto, the division of Jump Trading Group that was once run by Kanav K=
ariya:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late 2015,=C2=A0Jump=
=C2=A0had created=C2=A0a research and development office at its founders=E2=
=80=99 alma mater, sponsoring research projects and working with professors=
 on futuristic projects, like using virtual reality headsets to mimic tradi=
ng environments. They would also hire university students as interns, findi=
ng potential stars by word of mouth. A friend referred Kariya, who started =
as a student at Jump=E2=80=99s college satellite.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Jump=C2=A0had a conundrum. The firm needed to test the mettle =
of its would-be staffers=E2=80=94whether they could parse the nuances in fi=
nancial markets and translate them into algorithmic trading models. But it =
couldn=E2=80=99t give the temporary hires the keys to the kingdom, with its=
 proprietary strategies and billions of dollars in capital.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto offered a solution. The sector had its own tr=
adable assets, exchanges, and quirks, but it was separated enough from Jump=
=E2=80=99s world of stocks and bonds that it wouldn=E2=80=99t pose a threat=
. =E2=80=9CIt was a bit of a toy market,=E2=80=9D says one former employee,=
 who spoke with=C2=A0Fortune=C2=A0on the condition of anonymity to discuss =
their previous firm. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So when Kariya joi=
ned as an intern in January 2017, he was assigned to build early crypto tra=
ding infrastructure for the firm=E2=80=94with little oversight. =E2=80=9CWe=
 could just go out and do our own thing,=E2=80=9D he would tell a podcast i=
n January 2023. =E2=80=9CWork under this fully encapsulated bubble.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It feels like a usef=
ul mental model for crypto: Crypto is what you get when you take the smart =
ambitious interns at traditional financial firms and put them in charge of =
their own play=C2=A0market. Only for real money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">This is true in a deeper sense. In many cases, the essential attribut=
e of a crypto token is=C2=A0<em>liquidity:=C2=A0</em>What you want, often, =
is a token that trades a lot, because your goal for the token is to trade i=
t a lot. Real-world utility, a sensible business model,=C2=A0acceptance in =
real transactions, etc., are all less important than just=C2=A0<em>trading<=
/em>, if you think of=C2=A0crypto as a toy market for traders to play with.=
 If a token trades a lot at a high price, that in itself=C2=A0<em>justifies=
 </em>the price, because that is all that is asked of a token: It doesn=E2=
=80=99t need to have a good underlying business or cash flows; it just has =
to trade a lot=C2=A0at a high price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so=
 Jump was, for a while, critical to the crypto economy, because it was a bi=
g market maker, so it could ensure that tokens would trade a lot. Since tha=
t was what created value, Jump could=C2=A0<em>make=C2=A0</em>tokens valuabl=
e. In exchange for that service, token creators would give Jump some of the=
 tokens, and Jump would then have an incentive to make them valuable:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Token projects will lend market make=
rs a large supply of tokens so they can kickstart trading. Some firms also =
negotiate a call option, which gives the market makers the right to buy a c=
hunk of the tokens for a steep discount if the project goes well. Selig say=
s that the inverted structure in crypto=E2=80=94where market makers work wi=
th token projects, rather than exchanges=E2=80=94makes some sense, given pr=
ojects=E2=80=99 need to spur trading activity. It also creates dynamics tha=
t would never be allowed in TradFi. While crypto market makers still make m=
oney off the trading spreads, the massive windfalls often come from those l=
ucrative call options.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a firm lik=
e=C2=A0Jump, becoming the market maker for a token project meant unlimited =
upside with no real financial risk. =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re at=C2=A0Jump=
, you decide which one is going to win,=E2=80=9D one crypto exchange founde=
r tells=C2=A0Fortune, speaking on the condition of anonymity to discuss ind=
ustry dynamics.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Man, what a cr=
azy time the crypto boom was. It really did teach a generation of young fin=
ancial traders that they could build perpetual motion machines: You make a =
token, you trade it, that makes it go up, <em>the value comes from you trad=
ing it</em>, you can do no wrong, you get rich, =E2=80=9Cunlimited upside w=
ith no real financial risk.=E2=80=9D One token that Jump made valuable was =
Luna, which <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/361456=
13.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItM=
