</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Harvard University is basically in the=
 business of brand alliances. Harvard has a very strong academic brand, so=
=C2=A0that =E2=80=9CI went to Harvard=E2=80=9D is widely assumed to convey =
=E2=80=9CI am smart.=E2=80=9D (Disclosure, sorry, I went to Harvard.) But t=
hen it also wants to partner with other people who have other good but less=
 academic brands: It wants=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>people to be associated =
with Harvard not because they have high test scores but because they are fa=
mous actors or great athletes or rich. Those people bring Harvard=E2=80=99s=
 brand to a wider audience, which helps Harvard attract smart students and =
famous professors who think =E2=80=9Cah cool I get to be around celebrities=
 and rich people, that will probably be fun and also good for my career.=E2=
=80=9D (The rich people also give Harvard money.) And the celebrities and r=
ich people=C2=A0<em>want </em>to attach their brand to Harvard=E2=80=99s, b=
ecause Harvard has that good academic brand, and people want to look smart.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trick is to do this in a way that is c=
ynical=C2=A0<em>enough</em>=C2=A0to maximize impact, but not <em>too=C2=A0<=
/em>cynical; you have to maintain the core academic brand.=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a fun <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/36145613.193392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjQtMDctMjIvdGhlLTEyLTAwMC1oYXJ2YXJkLWJ1c2luZXNzLWNsY=
